        content: 'Visual priming research demonstrates that images and text in your environment influence your behavior and mood, even when you are not consciously aware of them. Dr. John Bargh at Yale University conducted landmark priming studies showing that subtle environmental cues significantly affect attitudes and behavior. Research by Dr. Ap Dijksterhuis at Radboud University found that exposure to words related to positive traits (like "intelligent" or "capable") improved subsequent performance on cognitive tasks. Affirmation posters leverage this priming effect: every time you glance at an affirmation on your wall, even unconsciously, your brain processes it and subtly shifts your mental state. Over weeks and months, this passive exposure compounds into meaningful cognitive change.',
